$slot / $fill Gotchas

1. No colons in slot/fill names

`$name="view:sco"` does NOT match between `$slot` and `$fill`. TW silently fails — no error, just falls back to default content.

```
<!-- BROKEN — colon breaks matching -->
<$slot $name="view:sco"/>  +  <$fill $name="view:sco">

<!-- CORRECT — use hyphens -->
<$slot $name="view-sco"/>  +  <$fill $name="view-sco">
```

---

2. $slot inside \procedure does NOT find $fill from outer $transclude $tiddler=

This is the biggest gotcha. When a consumer transcludes a component tiddler with `$fill` content, `$slot` calls INSIDE a `\procedure` defined in that tiddler cannot find the fills.

```
<!-- Component tiddler: my-component.tid -->
\procedure my-view(element)
<$slot $name="my-slot" element=<<element>>>fallback</$slot>
\end

<!-- Body level: -->
BODY: <$slot $name="my-slot">fallback</$slot>         <!-- WORKS -->
PROC: <$transclude $variable="my-view" element="x"/>   <!-- DOES NOT WORK -->
```

Workarounds:

- Put `$slot` at body level with `<%if%>` type branching (vtabs pattern):
```
<%if [<type>match[sec]]%>
  <$slot $name="view-sec" element=<<element>>><<element>></$slot>
<%elseif [<type>match[act]]%>
  <$slot $name="view-act" element=<<element>>><<element>></$slot>
<%endif%>
```

- Transclude an intermediate tiddler (pills pattern) — `$slot` works across `$transclude $tiddler=` boundaries but not through bare `$transclude $variable=` from body level.

---

3. @scope CSS is Chrome-only

`@scope (.my-class) { ... }` does NOT work in Firefox. Use class-prefixed CSS instead:

```css
/* BROKEN in Firefox */
@scope (.my-component) {
  span { color: red; }
}

/* CORRECT — works everywhere */
.my-component span { color: red; }
```
